Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribe to the events on the `Window`:

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Created    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Created");
    window.Activated  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Activated");
    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Deactivated");
    window.Resumed    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Resumed");
    window.Stopped    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Stopped");
    window.Destroying += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Destroying");

    // iOS / Mac Catalyst only – includes state for later restoration
    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🪟 Backgrounding");

    return window;
}
```

**Typical flow:**

| Platform | Sequence |
|---|---|
| **Foreground** | `Created → Activated` |
| **Switch away** | `Deactivated → Stopped` |
| **Switch back** | `Resumed → Activated` |
| **Close** | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |

`Backgrounding` only fires on iOS/Mac Catalyst (between `Deactivated` and `Stopped`) and provides a `BackgroundingEventArgs` you can use to persist state.
